// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion Intergrations 2/ReactorCLI/Product Info Sheet.txt
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Product Info Sheet: ReactorCLIExecutive SummaryReactorCLI is the advanced command-line interface framework for the Fusion ecosystem. While standard parsers (like clap or structopt) focus solely on parsing string vectors, ReactorCLI is Context-Aware. It can dynamically resolve arguments from the distributed Supernova mesh, fall back to an interactive TUI wizard when arguments are missing, and automatically generate equivalent CLI parsers for Python and JavaScript consumers in polyglot projects.Product IdentityName: ReactorCLICrate: fusion-reactor-cliCodename: "Event Horizon"Core Philosophy: "Never fail on a missing argument; ask for it."Key Differentiators (The "Enhancements")Auto-Interactive Mode: If a user runs a command and forgets a required argument, ReactorCLI doesn't crash. It seamlessly launches a TUI prompt to ask for the value (v1/v3 only).Unified Source Resolution: Parses values in priority order: CLI Flags -> Environment Variables -> Fusion.toml -> Distributed Mesh Config -> TUI Prompt.Polyglot Export: A Rust CLI definition can export a cli.json schema, allowing Fusion Forge to auto-generate a matching Python argparse or Node Commander interface.Hardware-Gated Arguments: Specific flags can be conditionally enabled only if the runtime detects specific hardware (e.g., --gpu-layers is hidden if no GPU is present).Version CompatibilityReactorCLI adapts its behavior based on the target runtime:Featurev1 (Native)v2.0 (Nebula)v2.1 (Nebula+)v3 (Supernova)Parsing✅✅✅✅Interactive TUI✅❌ (Sandboxed)⚠️ (Host Proxy)✅Hardware Gating✅ (Local)❌✅ (Host Query)✅ (Cluster)Mesh Context❌❌❌✅Target AudienceDevOps Engineers: Building tools that need to run both in CI (non-interactive) and on developer laptops (interactive).Fusion Plugin Developers: Exposing configuration for WASM plugins.Hybrid App Builders: Needing consistent CLI interfaces across Rust, C++, and Python components.
